  '[{"type":"intro","dayNumber":6,"dayTitle":"Quieting the Racing Mind","goal":"Complete Day 6 with steady, consistent action.","estimatedMinutes":15},{"type":"lesson","title":"Today''s Focus","paragraphs":["Complete Day 6 with steady, consistent action."],"highlight":"Consistency compounds into long-term change."},{"type":"action_step","stepNumber":1,"title":"Morning Sunlight Exposure (10–20 Minutes)","instructions":["Within 30 minutes of waking, go outside and expose your eyes to natural daylight.","Step outside your home, balcony, or street.","Do not wear sunglasses.","Face the direction of the sky (not directly at the sun).","Stay outside for 10–20 minutes.","Try walking slowly while getting sunlight to strengthen your circadian rhythm signal.","Why this works","Morning sunlight resets the brain’s internal clock, helping your body release melatonin naturally at","night."],"whyThisWorks":"Small consistent actions reinforce stability and reduce automatic, stress-driven reactions."},{"type":"breathing_exercise","title":"Hydration + Nervous System Activation","instructions":"Immediately after sunlight, drink 500–700 ml of water. Then perform this breathing exercise. 10 Cycles of Physiological Sigh Inhale through nose Take a second short inhale Slowly exhale through mouth Repeat 10 times. This reduces stress hormones and calms the nervous system.","pattern":{"inhaleSeconds":4,"exhaleSeconds":6},"cycles":10},{"type":"exercise_routine","title":"Morning Movement (sleep Pressure Builder)","exercises":[{"name":"Perform 10 Minutes Of Light Physical Movement.","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Brisk Walking","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Mobility Stretches","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Bodyweight Squats (15 Reps × 3)","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Pushups (10 Reps × 3)","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Movement Early In The Day Increases Sleep Pressure, Helping The Body Feel Naturally Tired At Night.","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]}]},{"type":"action_step","stepNumber":2,"title":"Caffeine Control Rule","instructions":["Follow this rule strictly:","No caffeine after 2 PM","This includes:","coffee","tea","energy drinks","pre-workout drinks","Caffeine can stay in the body 6–8 hours, delaying sleep onset."],"whyThisWorks":"Small consistent actions reinforce stability and reduce automatic, stress-driven reactions."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"Evening Nervous System Downshift","steps":["About 60 minutes before bed, listen to your guided sleep meditation audio.","Lie comfortably in bed.","Play the meditation audio at low volume.","Close your eyes and follow the instructions.","Allow your body to relax naturally.","Recommended length: 10–20 minutes."],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"Body Temperature Sleep Trick","steps":["Take a warm shower 60–90 minutes before sleep.","Why this works","After the shower, your body temperature naturally drops, which signals the brain to prepare for","sleep."],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"The Military Sleep Method (fast Sleep Technique)","steps":["Once in bed, do this:","Relax your forehead","Relax jaw and tongue","Drop shoulders completely","Slowly breathe out","Then imagine a calm scene:","You are lying in a quiet mountain valley at night.","The air is cool and peaceful.","Everything around you is still and calm.","Focus on the scene while breathing slowly.","Day 6 Sleep Trick – The “Brain Dump” Method","Many people cannot sleep because the brain keeps thinking about tasks, worries, or tomorrow’s","problems.","About 30 minutes before bed, take a notebook and write down:","everything on your mind","tasks for tomorrow","worries or thoughts","Do not organize it. Just empty your mind onto paper.","Why this works","The brain stays awake when it feels something important might be forgotten.","Writing things down tells the brain:","\"This is stored. I can relax now.\"","This often reduces racing thoughts dramatically at night.","Day 6 Goal","Reduce mental overload before bedtime, allowing the brain to relax and transition into sleep more","easily.","By Day 6 many people begin noticing:","quieter thoughts at night","less stress before sleep","falling asleep with less effort"],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"journal","prompt":"What helped you most on Day 6?","helperText":"Write one or two practical observations.","followUpPrompt":"What will you repeat tomorrow?"},{"type":"close","message":"Day 6 is complete.","secondaryMessage":"You reinforced quieting the racing mind today."}]'::jsonb
)
