breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"30 Reps × 5 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Pushups","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"22 Reps × 5 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Jumping Jacks","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"60 Reps × 4 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Plank Hold","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"50 Seconds × 5 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]}]},{"type":"action_step","stepNumber":2,"title":"Caffeine Control Rule","instructions":["Follow this rule strictly:","No caffeine after 2 PM","This includes:","coffee","tea","energy drinks","pre-workout drinks","Caffeine can remain active in the body 6–8 hours, disturbing sleep quality."],"whyThisWorks":"Small consistent actions reinforce stability and reduce automatic, stress-driven reactions."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"Evening Nervous System Downshift","steps":["About 60 minutes before bed, listen to your guided sleep meditation audio.","Lie comfortably in bed.","Play the meditation audio at low volume.","Close your eyes and follow the instructions.","Allow your body to relax naturally.","Recommended length: 10–20 minutes."],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"Body Temperature Sleep Trick","steps":["Take a warm shower 60–90 minutes before sleep.","Why this works","After the shower, your body temperature drops slightly, signaling the brain that it is time for sleep."],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"The Military Sleep Method (fast Sleep Technique)","steps":["Once in bed, do this:","Relax your forehead","Relax jaw and tongue","Drop shoulders completely","Slowly breathe out","Then imagine a calm scene:","You are lying beside a quiet river in the mountains.","The water flows gently and the night air is peaceful.","Focus on the calm scene while breathing slowly.","Day 19 Sleep Trick – The “Jaw Release Trick”","Many people hold hidden tension in the jaw muscles, which can keep the brain alert.","While lying in bed:","Slightly open your mouth.","Let your tongue relax at the bottom of your mouth.","Allow the jaw to feel loose and heavy.","Stay like this for 1–2 minutes.","Why this works","Jaw tension is connected to the brain’s stress response system.","Releasing the jaw sends a signal that the body is safe and ready for sleep.","Day 19 Goal","Release hidden muscle tension, allowing the body to enter deeper and more continuous sleep.","By Day 19 many people notice:","deeper relaxation before sleep","fewer nighttime awakenings","improved sleep continuity"],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"journal","prompt":"What helped you most on Day 19?","helperText":"Write one or two practical observations.","followUpPrompt":"What will you repeat tomorrow?"},{"type":"close","message":"Day 19 is complete.","secondaryMessage":"You reinforced releasing hidden body tension today."}]'::jsonb
)
