  '[{"type":"intro","dayNumber":21,"dayTitle":"Long-Term Sleep Stability","goal":"Complete Day 21 with steady, consistent action.","estimatedMinutes":21},{"type":"lesson","title":"Today''s Focus","paragraphs":["Complete Day 21 with steady, consistent action."],"highlight":"Consistency compounds into long-term change."},{"type":"action_step","stepNumber":1,"title":"Morning Sunlight Exposure (10–20 Minutes)","instructions":["Within 30 minutes of waking, go outside and expose your eyes to natural daylight.","Step outside your home, balcony, or street.","Do not wear sunglasses.","Face the direction of the sky (not directly at the sun).","Stay outside for 10–20 minutes.","Combine sunlight exposure with 10–15 minutes of walking.","Why this works","Morning sunlight keeps your circadian rhythm stable, helping the body release melatonin at the","correct time every night."],"whyThisWorks":"Small consistent actions reinforce stability and reduce automatic, stress-driven reactions."},{"type":"breathing_exercise","title":"Hydration + Nervous System Activation","instructions":"Immediately after sunlight, drink 500–700 ml of water. Then perform this breathing exercise. 10 Cycles of Physiological Sigh Inhale through nose Take a second short inhale Slowly exhale through mouth Repeat 10 times. This lowers stress hormones and prepares the nervous system for the day.","pattern":{"inhaleSeconds":4,"exhaleSeconds":6},"cycles":10},{"type":"exercise_routine","title":"Final Movement Routine (sleep Pressure Builder)","exercises":[{"name":"Total Movement Time: 50–55 Minutes","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Exercise Routine","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Brisk Walking","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"30 Minutes Continuous Walking.","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Bodyweight Squats","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"35 Reps × 6 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Pushups","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"25 Reps × 5 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Jumping Jacks","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"65 Reps × 5 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Plank Hold","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"60 Seconds × 5 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]}]},{"type":"action_step","stepNumber":2,"title":"Caffeine Control Rule","instructions":["Continue following this rule:","No caffeine after 2 PM","This includes:","coffee","tea","energy drinks","pre-workout drinks","Reducing late caffeine protects sleep quality and sleep depth."],"whyThisWorks":"Small consistent actions reinforce stability and reduce automatic, stress-driven reactions."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"Evening Nervous System Downshift","steps":["About 60 minutes before bed, listen to your guided sleep meditation audio.","Lie comfortably in bed.","Play the meditation audio at low volume.","Close your eyes and follow the instructions.","Allow your body to relax naturally.","Recommended length: 10–20 minutes."],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"Body Temperature Sleep Trick","steps":["Take a warm shower 60–90 minutes before sleep.","Why this works","After the shower, the body temperature drops slightly, signaling the brain that it is time for sleep."],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"The Military Sleep Method (fast Sleep Technique)","steps":["Once in bed, do this:","Relax your forehead","Relax jaw and tongue","Drop shoulders completely","Slowly breathe out","Then imagine a calm scene:","You are lying beside a quiet lake under a clear night sky.","The water is still and the night air is peaceful.","Focus on the calm scene while breathing slowly.","Day 21 Sleep Trick – The “Sleep Anchor”","This technique helps the brain associate one consistent cue with sleep.","Choose one simple action you will repeat every night before sleep, such as:","turning on your meditation audio","dimming the lights","taking 5 slow breaths","Repeat the same action every night before sleeping.","Why this works","The brain begins to associate that action with sleep time.","Over time, the brain will start triggering sleep almost automatically when the cue happens.","Day 21 Goal","Lock in the sleep habits and routines developed during the past 21 days so they continue working","long term.","By the end of the program many people notice:","consistent sleep timing","deeper sleep cycles","easier sleep onset","improved morning energy"],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"journal","prompt":"What helped you most on Day 21?","helperText":"Write one or two practical observations.","followUpPrompt":"What will you repeat tomorrow?"},{"type":"close","message":"Day 21 is complete.","secondaryMessage":"You reinforced long-term sleep stability today."}]'::jsonb
)
